Project 3: PCB & Component Visual Inspector - Complete Explanation
What the Project Does
This project is a computer vision application that identifies electronic components from photographs. Think of it as a visual search engine for circuit boards. When an electronics technician, quality control inspector, or repair shop worker uploads a picture of a component, the system analyzes the image and tells them what the component most likely is, along with a confidence score indicating how sure the AI is about its identification. For example, if someone takes a photo of a small cylindrical component with colored bands, the system might identify it as a resistor with 92 percent confidence. If the component is a small rectangular black chip with multiple metal legs, the system might identify it as an integrated circuit. This capability is extremely valuable in electronics manufacturing, repair, and recycling operations where workers need to quickly identify unknown components.

How the Computer Vision Works
The system uses a powerful artificial intelligence model called Vision Transformer, or ViT for short, which was developed by Google. Unlike traditional computer vision models that look at images pixel by pixel, the Vision Transformer divides the image into small patches, similar to cutting a photograph into a grid of tiny squares. It then analyzes how these patches relate to each other, similar to how the DistilBERT model from the previous projects analyzes how words relate to each other in a sentence. This approach has proven to be very effective for image classification tasks. The specific model used in this project, called vit-base-patch16-224, was pre-trained on a massive dataset called ImageNet containing over 14 million images across 20 thousand different categories. While ImageNet includes everyday objects like dogs, cars, and furniture, it also includes many electronic components, making it useful for this application even without additional fine-tuning.

Preprocessing and Image Handling
Before the AI can analyze an image, the system performs some important preprocessing steps. First, it converts any image to RGB color format. This is necessary because some smartphone cameras save images in different color formats, and some images might have an alpha transparency channel that the model cannot process. Second, the system creates a smaller copy of the image for display purposes, resizing it to fit neatly in the web interface while preserving the original aspect ratio so components do not appear stretched or distorted. The actual ViT model requires images to be a specific size of 224 by 224 pixels, but the Gradio pipeline handles this resizing automatically behind the scenes, so the user does not need to worry about preparing their images in any special way.

The User Interface
The application presents a visually clean web interface designed for workshop and factory environments. The main element is a large image upload area where users can drag and drop a photo, click to browse their files, or even use their computer's webcam to take a picture directly. This webcam feature is particularly useful for repair shops where workers can simply point a laptop or external camera at a component and capture the image without needing to save files first. A slider allows the user to control how many predictions the system should return, from one to ten. Below the image input, a large analyze button triggers the classification. The results appear in two forms on the right side of the screen. First, a colorful bar chart shows the top predictions with their confidence percentages, making it easy to see at a glance which identification is most likely. Second, a text summary explains the top result in plain English and rates the confidence as very high, high, moderate, or low.

Example Scenarios
Consider three typical use cases for this application. In the first scenario, a quality control inspector at an electronics assembly plant in Douala, Cameroon, finds a component that fell off the production line and needs to verify its identity before returning it to the correct bin. She places the component under a document camera, captures an image, and uploads it to the system. Within seconds, the system identifies the component as a 10k ohm resistor with 96 percent confidence and lists capacitor and inductor as lower-probability alternatives. The inspector confidently returns the component to the resistor bin, preventing a costly manufacturing error. In the second scenario, a repair shop technician in Lagos's Alaba market receives a damaged circuit board with several burned components that are no longer readable. He uses his phone to photograph the board, uploads the image, and the system identifies the burned components as voltage regulators based on their package shape and pin arrangement, allowing him to order the correct replacement parts. In the third scenario, a solar installation company in Nairobi uses a drone to inspect hard-to-reach panels and inverters. The drone captures images, which are automatically uploaded to the system to identify damaged or failed components without requiring a human to climb the structure.

The Technology Behind It
The system is built using the same core libraries as the previous projects. The transformers library from HuggingFace provides the Vision Transformer model with just one line of code, demonstrating how modern AI libraries have made computer vision accessible to any programmer. The Pillow library, imported as PIL, handles all the image processing tasks such as converting color formats and resizing. The gradio library creates the entire web interface, including the image upload area, webcam support, slider, button, label output with automatic bar chart rendering, and text output. The torch library runs the deep learning model efficiently on the user's computer. Unlike cloud-based vision APIs that charge per image and require internet connectivity, this entire application runs locally, meaning it can be used in remote workshops and factories that may have limited or no internet access.

African Engineering Context
This project was designed with several African manufacturing and repair scenarios in mind. In Cameroon, electronics assembly small and medium enterprises can use the system for quality control, ensuring that the correct components are placed on each circuit board before soldering. In Nigeria's Alaba market, one of West Africa's largest electronics markets, repair shop workers can identify unknown components from discarded electronics, salvaging valuable parts for reuse. In Kenya, drone inspection companies can automatically analyze images of solar panel installations to identify damaged or degrading components without sending technicians onto roofs. In Ghana, manufacturers producing electronics for export can use the system to verify that all components meet quality standards before shipping products to international buyers. The system is particularly valuable in contexts where specialized component identification equipment is too expensive and where access to expert component knowledge is limited.

Limitations and Future Improvements
The current system uses a general-purpose Vision Transformer model trained on everyday images, not specifically on electronic components. While the model performs reasonably well because ImageNet contains many electronics categories, it can make mistakes on rare or unusual components. In a production environment, the model should be fine-tuned on thousands of images of the specific components used by the factory or repair shop, which would dramatically improve accuracy. Additionally, the current system only identifies components but does not verify whether they are placed correctly or soldered properly. A future enhancement could detect soldering defects such as cold joints, bridges, or insufficient solder. Another improvement would be to add a barcode or QR code reader so that components with readable labels could be identified with perfect accuracy without relying on visual appearance alone. Finally, the system could be extended to count components on a board and verify that all expected components are present, providing automated quality assurance for assembly lines.

